<i>Posted by AugustinPenner on 05-24-2003 01:46 PM:</i>

<p><b> </b></p>

<p>I had a case in school once - I was 12 years old back then. A friend of my mothers from Japan gave us a diskette (Mac formatted) with games on it. There were some files tho, that we couldnt seem to open. Since we had macs in our school back then too, I decided to look up on what the remaining files are, my mom also told me to since she was curious.<br />
So I went to the computer lab and opened the file - a friend ofmine was sitting next to me. The file was some picture format file of a girl peeing that the guy in Japan forgot to delete off the disk. Well, I thought it was highly amusing (not arousing, I was 12 mind me) and decided to print it to show to my mom.<br />
The comp-lab supervisor came up to me with the picture, and started interrogating; confiscating the disk. He sent me away, and the case was told to my homeroom teacher, head of computer department, head of year, head of middle school AND director of school, and this was a private school.<br />
My parents had to write a letter of apology and explanation to the school. The funniest was tho, when my homeroom teacher (who hated my guts) came up to me a month after the whole thing was passé, sat down with me and started saying "Come on, we know you aren't that type of kid" etc...and I told her the whole thing was settled which she didnt believe, so I had to ask my parents AGAIN to print out ANOTHER copy of the excuse letter.</p>

<!-- END TEMPLATE: printthreadbit --><!-- BEGIN TEMPLATE: printthreadbit -->
<hr>
<i>Posted by lPLAZl on 05-24-2003 07:30 PM:</i>

<p><b> </b></p>

<p>(To Augustin)  Even at twelve years old, I couldn't think of anyone stupid enough to print out a picture of some naked chick peeing at school.  I bet that is what your homeroom teacher was thinking when she questioned you.  Ask yourself if you really did print it to be funny.  Did you actually use your excuse so much that you began to think it true?<br />
<br />
People must understand that schools need to have strict rules when it comes to obsenity.  Sure there may be the exception (kid gets suspended for going to whitehouse.com, or son isn't allowed to look up "condom"), but those rules are generally good.  If nobody in the school cared what your kids did, how good would you feel about sending him or her there every day when you know that they could be surfing porn during library time?<br />
<br />
The benifits in this case severilty outweigh the consequences.<br />
<br />
Camaris, I grant you that I am no father.  However, like you, I was a kid once and went through the whole high-school thing.  Now at fifteen years old, your son is either a freshy or a sophmore.  Ask your son why he wanted to research the condom.  Of all the things he could have done, why the condom?  I would bet my bottom dollar he did it to be funny because he knew the subject was a bit "funny."<br />
<br />
Kids in school are encouraged to take their projects seriously.  You research something that interests you so that you may learn.  While your son may have been interested in the condom (watch him closely if so), most likely he just did it for the toilet humor aspect.  <br />
<br />
Why do I stack such odds against him?  Because I remember my Freshman and Sophmore years, and I don't think I can remember anyone who would research condoms (or viagra or the pill) and keep a straight face doing it.  Those projects are supposed to be serious.<br />
<br />
The project on LSD is just as bad and the school should have blocked that material as well.  <br />
<br />
--I am no way trying to bash either of you here.  I am just giving my [opposite] opinion of your situations.<!-- BEGIN TEMPLATE: postbit_signature -->
