<i>Posted by AugustinPenner on 05-25-2003 06:02 AM:</i>

<p><b> </b></p>

<p>Now that you say it, you prolly are right Plaz. But what happened, happened, and I learnt not to do it (which is in the end what really counts).<br />
My memory of my past is very blurred because of a few issues I had, but thats passé (I hope). Anyway, I actually do agree to you Plaz, now that I think back, I remember actually not trying to laugh and act grown-up and all mature during biology classes...well everyone was trying it...but I don't think any parent should take it seriously.<br />
I mean, c'mon...many of us didn't take school serious at times, and there should be no reason to watch a kid closely just because of that. It's normal, and it belongs to growth.<br />
But there are always 2 sides to a coin, and you can't really generalize all kids. Some might actually take it more serious when you put a close eye on them, and some might rebel and shoot the completely opposite direction - remember, puberty is partially a time of claiming independance of parents. Hell I rebelled badly too, even stormed out of the house and didn't come back a while - out of protest.<br />
I think, in the end, every parent has to get to know his/her own kid well enough during childhood (hence spend a lot of time with him/her) to learn how to treat him/her throughout puberty. And still then, the average normal kid will rebel...shit im contradicting myself...too many thoughts developing on this matter. I'll keep it at this.</p>

